Update this file to keep note of how to maintain this repo!

<EarlyStageDatabase>
- During initial bootstrap, if the Neon database is empty, prefer resetting Drizzle migration history and re-baselining from Better Auth generated schema instead of layering rename/fix-up migrations.
</EarlyStageDatabase>

<Auth>
- Keep Better Auth organization roles, custom access-control statements, and Drizzle auth schema changes in sync across `lib/auth.ts`, `lib/auth-client.ts`, and `lib/auth/permissions.ts`.
- Treat `organizationId` as the tenant boundary on business tables and keep cross-org sharing disabled unless there is an explicit product requirement and server-side enforcement plan.
- Keep `/` aligned with Better Auth active organization state so signed-in users resume in their latest visited workspace instead of falling back to the public landing page.
</Auth>

<Payments>
- Select provider with `PAYMENT_PROVIDER=stripe|polar`; canonical plans and env-mapped price/product IDs live in `lib/payments/plans.ts`.
- Billing domain logic stays in `lib/payments/*`; routes under `app/api/billing/*` and `app/api/payments/webhooks/*` are thin adapters. Use `lib/billing-client.ts` from the browser for checkout/portal/access/sync.
- Webhooks must use the raw request body for signature verification; store each provider event idempotently in `billing_event` before syncing (`lib/payments/repository.ts`).
- After changing `lib/db/schema/billing.ts`, run `bun run db:generate` and apply migrations; document new env vars in `.env.example`.
</Payments>

<Logging>
- Use `@/lib/logger` instead of raw `console.*` in app code so logs stay structured and level-aware.
- Create scoped loggers with `logger.child({ scope: "feature.area" })` near the entry point you are working in.
- Prefer stable human-readable messages plus structured metadata as the second argument.
- Use `trace`/`debug` for local diagnostics, `info` for normal lifecycle events, `warn` for recoverable anomalies, `error` for failures, and `fatal` only for unrecoverable startup or shutdown paths.
- Never log secrets, auth tokens, passwords, cookies, raw authorization headers, or full request bodies that may contain sensitive data.
- Control verbosity with the `LOG_LEVEL` environment variable instead of sprinkling temporary logs through the codebase.
</Logging>

<ExternalIntegrations>
- Keep reusable protocol logic for third-party systems in `lib/<integration>/` modules, and keep Next.js/tRPC/request-context concerns in thin adapters.
</ExternalIntegrations>

<Frontend>
- When using `next-themes` with React 19 / Next 16, mount-gate theme-dependent icons and labels to avoid hydration mismatches, and treat the React `<script>` warning from `next-themes` as an upstream false positive until the package ships a fix.
</Frontend>

<CodeHygiene>
- Prefer `@/lib/try-catch` for result-style async handling in UI submit flows and thin server adapters; keep explicit `try/catch` for rollback-centric transactional paths.
- Prefer `@/lib/error-utils` for user-safe unknown-error formatting instead of duplicating ad hoc `getErrorMessage` helpers per component.
</CodeHygiene>

<Analytics>
- PostHog is the product analytics layer: client init lives in root `instrumentation-client.ts` (reverse-proxied via `next.config.ts` `/ph/*` → EU Cloud). Do not log secrets, tokens, or PII in event properties.
- Server-side capture uses `posthog-node` from `@/lib/analytics/posthog-server` (`createPostHogServerClient`, `captureServerEvent`) with `POSTHOG_HOST` (default `https://eu.i.posthog.com`) — never point the Node client at the `/ph` rewrite. Client components import `@/lib/analytics` only for `trackClientEvent` / `AnalyticsEvents` (no server re-exports in the barrel).
- Identity and organization groups are handled by `components/analytics/posthog-identify.tsx` (Better Auth session → `identify` + `group`). Logged-in users are opted in to capturing; anonymous visitors see `CookieConsentBanner` and must accept before tracking.
- On sign-out, call `posthog.reset()` after `authClient.signOut()` (see `components/site-header.tsx`) so the PostHog person session clears with the auth session.
- Env: `NEXT_PUBLIC_POSTHOG_KEY`, `NEXT_PUBLIC_POSTHOG_HOST` (usually `/ph`), optional `POSTHOG_HOST` for server ingest.
- Default template events (names in `lib/analytics/event-names.ts`): `signup:began`, `signup:completed`, `signup:verified` (server), `auth:signed_in`, `auth:signed_out`, `org:created`, `org:switched`, `invite:accepted`. Keep properties minimal and never include PII (email, name, tokens).
</Analytics>
